  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 2528d50a14eba0c4abfe3aafdf2a2b70, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::Utilities.LevelReadme
  levelName: 'Inventory System: Clean Architecture & Object Pooling'
  description: "This mini-game serves as a technical showcase of advanced software
    architecture in Unity, focusing on scalability, clean code, and memory optimization.
    \r\nThe system implements a Minecraft-style inventory with the following engineering
    pillars:\r\n1. Model-View Architecture (Observer Pattern): Strict separation
    of concerns. The 'InventoryModel' handles all business logic (adding, removing,
    splitting, and merging items) purely via C# arrays. The 'InventoryView' and 'SlotView'
    are \"dumb\" presentation layers that only react to C# Action events, completely
    decoupling logic from the UI.\r\n2. Zero GC & Object Pooling: The system guarantees
    zero garbage collection spikes during runtime. UI elements are generated dynamically
    using Unity's native 'UnityEngine.Pool.ObjectPool', allowing the inventory to
    scale infinitely without performance drops.\r\n3. Data-Driven Design: Items are
    strictly defined as ScriptableObjects ('ItemData'), centralizing configuration
    (ID, Icon, Max Stack Size) and preventing memory duplication across the grid.\r\n4.
    SOLID Principles: The codebase adheres strictly to the Single Responsibility
    Principle and Dependency Inversion, making the logic fully modular and testable
    without a Canvas."
  controls: "- [1], [2], [3] Keys: Inject test items (Dirt, Stone, Wood) into the
    model.\r\n- [Backspace] Key: Remove an item from the first slot.\r\n- Mouse Left
    Click (Hold & Drag): Drag and drop items between slots. \r\n  * Dragging to an
    empty slot moves the stack.\r\n  * Dragging to a matching item merges the stacks
    (respecting the Max Stack Size limits).\r\n- Mouse Right Click: Automatically
    splits the hovered stack in half and sends it to the nearest available empty
    slot."
